nowFeed.headline: The season-ending loss to the Raiders Sunday put the Broncos at 8-9, their eighth consecutive playoff miss and seventh consecutive losing season. S Justin Simmons, the longest-tenured Broncos player, has been there for them all. It hurts ... it stinks, it's a bitter feeling right now ... It hurts to go out like that, especially when you wanted to win.'' Simmons later added: There's definitely positives for the season, but there were definitely goals that weren't hit.''
nowFeed.story: The season-ending loss to the Raiders Sunday put the Broncos at 8-9, their eighth consecutive playoff miss and seventh consecutive losing season. S Justin Simmons, the longest-tenured Broncos player, has been there for them all. It hurts ... it stinks, it's a bitter feeling right now ... It hurts to go out like that, especially when you wanted to win.'' Simmons later added: There's definitely positives for the season, but there were definitely goals that weren't hit.''

nowFeed.headline: After the 27-14 loss to the Raiders in Las Vegas that put the Broncos at 8-9 for the season's end, coach Sean Payton on the performance: “Thought we lost in a lot of areas tonight, thought they ran it better than us, they protected better than us, our quarterback was under a lot more duress than theirs.’’ Payton also said he told the players “(I) reminded them just remember how this feels.'' Broncos rushed for 48 yards and quarterback Jarrett Stidham was sacked five times.

nowFeed.headline: The Seahawks ruled out RT Abe Lucas, DE Mario Edwards, RG Phil Haynes and RB Kenny McIntosh for their regular-season finale at Arizona. LB Jordyn Brooks is questionable, but Pete Carroll expects him to play. Carroll said NT Jarran Reed will be a game-time decision and that Jason Peters, also questionable, isn't expected to play. With No Lucas and likely no Peters, Stone Forsythe is in line to start at RT. RB Ken Walker III has no game designation and had a very good week, per Carroll.

nowFeed.headline: Seahawks LB Jordyn Brooks went from limited on Wednesday to a non-participant Thursday -- one of Seattle's eight DNPs -- because of his injured ankle, so his status for the regular-season finale at Arizona remains in question. nowFeed.headline: RB Ken Walker III was one of seven Seahawks who didn't practice Wednesday, but that looks like maintenance. Pete Carroll said Walker made it out of the Steelers game OK with his banged-up shoulder and that he feels better than he did this time last week. Carroll said Abe Lucas' knee is really bothering him. He doesn't expect Lucas or Jason Peters to play this week, meaning Stone Forsythe is in line to start at RT. LB Jordyn Brooks, trying to get back from his ankle injury, was limited.
